<div class="wrap">
  <section class="hero">
    <span class="eyebrow">About</span>
    <h1>What this is</h1>
    <p class="thesis">The Mexico Brief is a site about Mexico. Mostly the economy, politics, and the relationship with the US. I keep finding other things to add.</p>
    <p>I pull together data from Banxico, INEGI, Hacienda, and other original sources and put it in one place. The peso, inflation, wages, trade, public finances, polling, crime, energy, and so on.</p>
    <p>Some numbers update every day. Others update once a year. Government statistics do not, unfortunately, run on my preferred schedule.</p>
    <p>Data is not the whole story. Obviously. But it is a much better place to start than a headline telling me what to think. I add the news that helps explain what may be happening. When I have my own view, I say so.</p>
    <p>Having it all together has been more useful than I expected. Wages make more sense next to inflation. Trade looks different next to the peso. Economic growth is worth looking at next to government approval. Those numbers normally live on completely different websites.</p>
    <p>Everything is dated and linked to the original source. You can check it, go deeper, and come to your own conclusion. If you disagree with mine, even better.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="blk">
    <h2>Why I built it</h2>
    <p>My name is <b>Alan Lacroix</b>. I was born in Mexico City and moved to Miami when I was young. My Spanish is great. My Mexican accent, on the other hand&hellip; más o menos.</p>
    <p>I'm building a business in Mexico now and visit often. Somewhere along the way I realized I had lost touch with the country's social, political, and especially economic reality.</p>
    <p>The peso was at 17.5. Good or bad? The minimum wage had gone up how much? Supermajority? How much of Mexico's economy depends on the US? These felt like things I should probably know.</p>
    <p>I kept ending up on ten different websites just to find the original numbers. Government portals, databases, PDFs, press releases. Mexico produces a surprising amount of useful data. It does not always make it easy to find.</p>
    <p>The news did not help much. Too many headlines, in both directions, started with the conclusion. I wanted the information first and then I could make up my own mind.</p>
    <p>So I started putting it all in one place.</p>
    <p>I built the Brief for myself. I found it extremely useful, started sharing it with family and friends, and they did too. So I opened it up.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="blk">
    <h2>Why should you trust me?</h2>
    <p class="lead-line">Don't. Kidding. Sort of.</p>
    <p>I do not think you should trust a clean website or a confident paragraph just because it looks official. There is too much nonsense online for that.</p>
    <p>Every number shows the date and links to where it came from. If it came from Banxico, INEGI, or Hacienda, you can open the original release. If I calculated it from the data, it says derived and shows the inputs. If it came from a news report, it says reported. If it is my opinion, you will know.</p>
    <p>The point is not for you to take my word for it. The point is that you can check me.</p>
    <p>If a feed stops updating, its last value stays on the site with the date. I would rather show an old number as old than make it look current.</p>
    <p>Also, my name is on the site and so is my reputation. If I get something wrong, please tell me.</p>
    <p>I have no affiliation with any government or political party. Nothing here is investment advice.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="blk">
    <h2>The email</h2>
    <p>Once a week, I send the few things that changed in Mexico's economy, politics, and relationship with the US that I think are worth knowing.</p>
    <p>I look at the numbers, add the news that helps explain them, and tell you what I think. The original sources are there if you want to go deeper.</p>
    <p>Honestly, my dad could never remember the name of the site, so sending it directly to his inbox was easier. It seems to work well for other people too.</p>
    <p><a class="abtn" href="/weekly.html">See what's in it and subscribe &rarr;</a></p>
  </section>

  <section class="blk">
    <h2>Things I'm interested in</h2>
    <p><b>Economic growth.</b> Mexico sits next to the largest economy in the world and trades with it more than anyone. Why have we not grown faster?</p>
    <p><b>Politics.</b> Stability, institutions, and what actually matters after the headline passes.</p>
    <p><b>The US&ndash;Mexico relationship.</b> Trade, migration, security, and the millions of businesses and families that live across both countries. I view Mexico partly through a US lens. This is the obvious one for me.</p>
    <p><b>Technology and AI.</b> Everyone has an AI strategy now. I want to know whether Mexico is actually using it, where it has an advantage, and what it means for services, factories, and jobs.</p>
    <p><b>Capital and entrepreneurship.</b> Private equity, venture capital, family businesses, and the people building companies in Mexico. I am now one of the people trying.</p>
    <p><b>Football.</b> We always qualify, get our hopes up, and usually go out at the first knockout round. Best jersey though. We have them next time. Maybe 2030.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="blk">
    <h2>Tell me what I'm missing</h2>
    <p>This is still a work in progress. I keep finding new sources, missing data, and better ways to show something.</p>
    <p>If a number looks wrong, something does not make sense, or you know a source I should add, please tell me.</p>
    <p class="sign">Alan</p>
  </section>
